{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Surface Mapping Using Fiducial Markers and Screen Corners\n",
    "\n",
    "## What are Fiducial Markers?\n",
    "\n",
    "Fiducial markers (for a review see [<sup>1</sup>](https://doi.org/10.1007/s10846-020-01307-9)) are specially designed visual patterns that serve as reference points for establishing coordinate correspondence. They are reliably detected in images, enabling transformation between image/video coordinates and real-world coordinates. In eye-tracking, they allow us to transform gaze from the camera's perspective to the observed surface (for example, a computer screen).\n",
    "\n",
    "PyNeon supports two widely-adopted marker systems:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **[AprilTag](https://april.eecs.umich.edu/software/apriltag)** (references<sup>[2](https://doi.org/10.1109/ICRA.2011.5979561),[3](https://doi.org/10.1109/IROS.2016.7759617)</sup>): Also used by [Pupil Labs Neon Player](https://docs.pupil-labs.com/neon/neon-player/surface-tracker/) and [Pupil Cloud](https://docs.pupil-labs.com/neon/pupil-cloud/enrichments/marker-mapper/).\n",
    "\n",
    "- **[ArUco](https://www.uco.es/investiga/grupos/ava/portfolio/aruco/)** (reference<sup>[4](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.patcog.2014.01.005)</sup>): Integrated into OpenCV, enabling marker detection via [cv2.aruco](https://docs.opencv.org/4.x/d5/dae/tutorial_aruco_detection.html).\n",
    "\n",
    "<p><a href=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Comparison_of_augmented_reality_fiducial_markers.svg#/media/File:Comparison_of_augmented_reality_fiducial_markers.svg\"><img src=\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/81/Comparison_of_augmented_reality_fiducial_markers.svg\" alt=\"Comparison of augmented reality fiducial markers.svg\" width=\"600\"/></a>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Sample Dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "We use a sample dataset called \"markers\" containing two recordings: one with AprilTag markers and one with ArUco markers. In both, a participant viewed artworks on a computer screen. Specifically, the participant moved their head often to test robustness under larger head motion. We will map gaze and fixation data onto the screen using markers visible in the scene video. The sample data is fetched via `get_sample_data(...)` and stored locally after download."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from pyneon import Dataset, get_sample_data\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "# Load a sample recording\n",
    "dataset_dir = get_sample_data(\"markers\", format=\"cloud\")\n",
    "dataset = Dataset(dataset_dir)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's start with the AprilTag recording (recording index 0)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",

      "Wearer ID: 028e4c69-f333-4751-af8c-84a09af079f5\n",
      "Wearer name: Pilot\n",
      "Recording start time: 2025-09-22 00:25:14.096000\n",
      "Recording duration: 244820000000 ns (244.82 s)\n",
      "\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "rec = dataset.recordings[0]\n",
    "print(rec)"
   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## AprilTag Example\n",
    "\n",
    "### Visualizing Markers in Video\n",
    "\n",
    "First, inspect a few frames to confirm the markers are clearly visible and well lit. Below are three example frames: fixation cross, artwork presentation, and inter-trial interval."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x300 with 3 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "video = rec.scene_video\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(12, 3))\n",
    "video.plot_frame(380, ax=axs[0], show=False)\n",
    "video.plot_frame(500, ax=axs[1], show=False)\n",
    "video.plot_frame(520, ax=axs[2], show=False)\n",
    "axs[0].set_title(\"Fixation\")\n",
    "axs[1].set_title(\"Image\")\n",
    "axs[2].set_title(\"ISI\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Step 1: Detect Markers\n",
    "\n",
    "The `detect_markers()` method automatically detects AprilTag or ArUco markers. The only required argument is `marker_family` (for example, `'36h11'` for AprilTag tag36h11, omitting \"tag\").\n",
    "\n",
    "Optional parameters allow customization:\n",
    "- `processing_window`: restrict detection to a specific time range\n",
    "- `processing_window_unit`: interpret the window as frames, seconds, or timestamps\n",
    "- `step`: process every Nth frame to speed up detection\n",
    "- `detector_parameters`: pass custom `cv2.aruco.DetectorParameters` for fine-tuning\n",
    "- `undistort`: optionally undistort frames before detection\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we use default settings, processing all frames:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from pathlib import Path\n",
    "from pyneon import Stream\n",
    "import os\n",
    "\n",
    "detection_path = Path(\"export\") / \"detected_markers.csv\"\n",
    "if detection_path.exists():\n",
    "    detected_markers = Stream(detection_path)\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    os.makedirs(detection_path.parent, exist_ok=True)\n",
    "    detected_markers = video.detect_markers(\"36h11\", step=5)\n",
    "    detected_markers.save(detection_path)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Verifying Detection\n",
    "\n",
    "Detected markers are stored in a PyNeon `Stream` with timestamps from the video frames. Each row corresponds to a detection and includes the marker id and corner coordinates in the video frame."
   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Step 2: Define Real-World Marker Coordinates\n",
    "\n",
    "To establish the mapping, provide a dataframe with real-world coordinates for each marker. This requires:\n",
    "- **Marker name**: must match the ids reported by `detect_markers()`\n",
    "- **Center coordinates**: where the marker is located in the target surface coordinate system (here, screen pixels)\n",
    "- **Size**: physical marker size in the same units as the target surface\n",
    "\n",
    "In this experiment (screen resolution 2560x1440), markers were placed near the screen corners with a 50 px margin and 200x200 px size. They are also placed in a clockwise order, starting from the top-left corner.\n",
    "\n",
    "Once a `marker_info` dataframe is defined, we can preview it to make sure the coordinates look correct using the `plot_marker_layout()` function:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "  marker name  size  center x  center y\n",
      "0     36h11_0   200       150     150.0\n",
      "1     36h11_1   200      2410     150.0\n",
      "2     36h11_2   200      2410     720.0\n",
      "3     36h11_3   200      2410    1290.0\n",
      "4     36h11_4   200       150    1290.0\n",
      "5     36h11_5   200       150     720.0\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from pyneon.vis import plot_marker_layout\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "\n",
    "width = 2560\n",
    "height = 1440\n",
    "marker_layout = pd.DataFrame(\n",
    "    {\n",
    "        \"marker name\": [f\"36h11_{i}\" for i in range(6)],\n",
    "        \"size\": 200,\n",
    "        \"center x\": [150, width - 150, width - 150, width - 150, 150, 150],\n",
    "        \"center y\": [150, 150, height / 2, height - 150, height - 150, height / 2],\n",
    "    }\n",
    ")\n",
    "print(marker_layout)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))\n",
    "plot_marker_layout(marker_layout, ax=ax, show_marker_names=True, show=False)\n",
    "ax.set_xlim(0, width)\n",
    "ax.set_ylim(height, 0)\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Step 3: Compute Homography Transformation\n",
    "\n",
    "The `find_homographies()` method computes a frame-by-frame 2D transformation (homography) between detected marker locations and their real-world coordinates. The result is a `Stream` of 3x3 homography matrices, one per frame where enough markers are available. These matrices enable mapping any point from camera coordinates to screen coordinates."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Computing surface-mapping homographies: 100%|| 1408/1408 [00:04<00:00, 294.15it/s]"
     ]
    },
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [

     ]
    },

     "name": "stderr",

   ],
   "source": [
    "from pyneon.video import find_homographies\n",
    "\n",
    "homographies = find_homographies(\n",
    "    detected_markers,\n",
    "    layout=marker_layout,\n",
    ")\n",
    "print(homographies.data.head())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Step 4: Apply Transformation to Gaze Data\n",
    "\n",
    "Now apply the homography transformation to project gaze and fixations onto screen coordinates. This is done using the `apply_homographies()` method of gaze and fixation objects. Internally, PyNeon interpolates the homographies to the timestamps of the gaze and fixation samples and applies the closest valid transform.\n",
    "\n",
    "You might notice warning messages. They are expected when homographies are missing for some frames (for example, markers were not visible or were blurred). If the nearest homography is too far from a sample time (default 500 ms), the sample is dropped. You can change this behavior with the `max_gap_ms` argument."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [

    "## Example 2: ArUco Markers\n",
    "\n",
    "The same workflow applies to ArUco markers. Instead of a family name, ArUco dictionaries are specified by their pattern (for example, `'5x5_50'`). The same four steps (detect, define coordinates, compute homography, transform) apply; only the marker family changes."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

     "name": "stderr",

     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Alternative: Contour-Based Screen-Corner Detection\n",
    "\n",
    "When fiducial markers are unavailable, estimate the homography from bright screen corners. The `detect_contour()` method looks for a bright rectangular contour per frame and returns its four corners. This works best when the screen is brighter than the background. You can tune `brightness_threshold`, `adaptive`, or `morph_kernel`, and use `step` or `processing_window` to speed up processing."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Detecting contour corners: 100%|| 1044/1044 [00:21<00:00, 48.54it/s]\n",
      "C:\\Users\\qian.chu\\Documents\\GitHub\\PyNeon\\pyneon\\tabular.py:67: UserWarning: Following columns not in known data types, using default data types: contour name\n",
      "  warn(\n",
      "Computing surface-mapping homographies: 100%|| 870/870 [00:00<00:00, 1514.39it/s]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from pyneon.video import find_homographies\n",
    "\n",
    "screen_detections = video.detect_contour()\n",
    "\n",
    "contour_layout = np.array(\n",
    "    [\n",
    "        [0, 0],\n",
    "        [width, 0],\n",
    "        [width, height],\n",
    "        [0, height],\n",
    "    ],\n",
    "    dtype=np.float32,\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "homographies_screen = find_homographies(\n",
    "    screen_detections,\n",
    "    layout=contour_layout,\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
